Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name in the case of the   Domesday Book   tenants from Beaufour (Calvados), which is recorded as  <i>Belfou</i>,  <i>Beaufou</i> in 1100 and as  <i>Bellefai</i> in about 1160 (   Tengvik  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Boffee","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["English: locative name from either of two places in Lancs, namely Bispham near Blackpool ( <i>Bischopham</i>, 1086 in   Domesday Book  ) or Bispham in Croston."]},{"name":"Buffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffy","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Tengvik","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name in the case of the   Domesday Book   tenants from Beaufour (Calvados), which is recorded as  <i>Belfou</i>,  <i>Beaufou</i> in 1100 and as  <i>Bellefai</i> in about 1160 (   Tengvik  )."]}]},{"name":"Ruchard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":89,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":98,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ruchard de Beaufou was born about 1126, in Wilton, Norfolk, England. She married Richard de Beaufou before 1140, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1126–":"umbes 1126–Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1126–Female":"1126–Surnud","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1224":"1224","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","Abt 1126":"umbes 1126","before 1140":"enne 1140","1207":"1207","Europe":"Europe","Wilton, Norfolk, England":"Wilton, Norfolk, England","Thatcham, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1126–":"noin 1126–K